{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_goosefoot_ver01/data/sn84036285/00340581829/1930091801/0703.xml":{"full_text":"Carbon County News\nI Published every Thursday at Rod Lodge, Carbon Co., Montana\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF CARBON COUNTY\nj OFFICIAL PAPER OF THE CITY OF RED LODGE, MONT.\nO. H. P. SHELLEY, Editor and Owner\nSubscription Per year,\n$2.50; six months, fl,50;\nthree months, $1. All sub\nscriptions payable in advance\nEntered at the Postoffice at\nRed Lodge, Montana, as Mat.\nter of the Second Class. Un\nder the Act of Congress of\nMarch 5, 1879.\nMem\nr\n\u00a3i>\nNational Editorial Association\nI Advertising rates based on guaranteed circulation and furnished\nI upon application. Discount given on contracts.\nfry 4\nAlto\nTELEPHONE NUMBER NINE\nGALEN FOR THE SENATE\nJUDGE ALBERT J. GALEN, as the candidate on\nthe republican ticket in Montana for the United St\nates senatorship, is a straightforward citizen, stand\ning ace high in the estimation of his fellowmen. His\nrecord as an official is like an open book that anyone\nrunning through may read with profit. His useful\nness as a public official has been proven. His con\ntinued service in behalf of the state is demanded by\nhis party. That opportunity is. afforded in his nomin\nation by the republican party as its candidate for the\nsenate.\nThrough the years that have taken Judge Galen\nfrom the status of a private citizen to a seat on the\nsupreme court bench, he has demonstrated his loyal\nty to the commonwealth. His decisions as a member\nof the high court have upheld the Volstead act, as an\ninstance, according to the law and in the intense ec\nonomic struggle now going on this state must look\nfirst to its own agricultural interests or fall behind in\npopulation and wmalth.\nTearing away much of the verbiage, the euologies\nof candidates, and the somewhat vague generaliza\ntions that appear in spots in the republican plat\nform, we think one thing stands out very clearly and\nought to be strsssd in the coming weeks; the impor\ntance of the declaration of support of the federal\nfarm board and inferentially a commendation of\nPresident in backing its chairman, Alexander Legge\nwho is fighting in the midst of a heavy dust storm\nto realize for the farmers of the nation a better and\nmore orderly marketing system.\nThe state of Kansas, no doubt one of the most\nfarm minded states in the union, supported Legge\nand repudiated a governor who opposed his efforts\nto this end. Surely Montana farmers .m\u00fcst be of the\nsame mind as their fellow farmers in that state. They\nmust realize' that setting up of this massive structure\nis not the work of a day, but inevitably the work of\nyears. They should not feel disillusioned if results\ndo not show at once when they stop to consider the\nJforces that are trying to discredit and down\nit\u2014the powerful private grain interests assailing him\nwith everything they have but that the democratic\npropaganda agencies at Washington and democratic\ndailies like the Great Falls Tribune are showing him\nno sympathetic consideration. If Legge loses, the\ncause of this enlightened marketing cooperative\nmovement will not again have a ghost of a chance\nfor at least a half a century because this generation\nwill not again see a leader of his like.\nSo what this paper concieves as the vital challenge\nof the republican party in Montana in this campaign\nis, stand by Hoover who is standing by Legge and\nthe federal farm act.\u2014-(Miles City Daily Star.)\n-o\nBUSINESS ON UPGRADE\nThere are already signs that a seasonal improve\nment in business will soon be underway. July and\nAugust are always the dull months of the year. This\nyear they were duller than usual on account of the de\npression which set in last year. Whether the season\nal improvement will develope into another business\nboom, even a mild boom, it is impossible to forecast.\nHowever it is encouraging to note that even the most\nconservative of business forecasters believe that 1981\nwill be a much better year than 1930. And it is to be\nkept in mind that 1930 suffers so greatly only because\nit is compared with the unusual business vear of 1929.\nAs compared with 1928 it makes a rather creditable\nshowing.\nDuring the long months of debate over the tariff\nbill, and especially during the closing weeks w hen it\nbecame evident that protetive measure would be pass\ned, importations to the United States were acceler\nated in order to get as many foreign goods into the\nAmerican market as possible before the new tariff\nbill went into effect. It js taking some time to absorb\nthis surplus, but it is being done slowly, more slowly\nthan would hav been the case, of course, if the coun\ntry had been in the midst of a boom.\nBut there are signs of business revival due directly\nto the tariff. The pottery business is an example.\nFor years American pottery products have ben un\nable to compete with their European competitors and\nmost of th plants have been closed down. The sched\nj nies in the new tariff law give the pottery industry\nsome relief and it is encouraging to note the predict\nions of the heads of the industry that operations will\nbe resumed in these American plants in the near fu\n1 ture.\nin tne meantime there is a worldwide depression in\nthe price of commodities. Sugar is now selling at\nunheard of low levels. In mam communities it can\nbe purchased at retail for less than five cents a po\ni und. Free trade orators gleefully refer to the slump\nin our foreign trade blaming it on to the tariff, al\nthough it set in months before the tariff bill was pass\ned. But they say nothing of the \"sob sister\" predict\nions they were making a few months ago to the ef\u25a0\nfeet that the increased sugar schedule would put a\nterrible burden on the market baskets of the house-,\nwives of America. Such remarks are now too silly\ni to be funny.\n0\nLOOKING UP\nWith Labor Day, 1930, now a holiday of the past,\nmost people are begining to look for much awaited\nseasonable improvement in business. That there will\nbe some such improvement is generally agreed to by\nall business observers, the conservative as well as the\noptimistic forecasters. Just how great it will be, and\nwhether it will be more than a seasonable improve\nment remains to be seen.\nAlready thre are signs of better times on the hor\nizon. Car loadings have been picking up for the past\ntwo or three weeks. There has been a stiffening in\ncommodity prices, with a few notable exceptions, and\nbest of all the intense feeling of pessimism which\nswept over the country through the dull summer\nmonths is gradually receding, and while all are not\noptimiste, those who are not so, are more or less\ncomplacent in the belief that the worst is over.\nThere are several signs that things are going to be\nbetter. First and perhaps most important is the fact\nthat during the past few months production has been\ncurtailed so drastically that it has run behind con\nsumption. For this reason surplus stocks of goods\nhave been gradually been cut down until now, it is\npredicted that any sort of a stimulated demand will\nbe a signal for considerably stimulated production.\nAnd although production has fallen below consump\ntion, the people are buying \"from hand to mouth\" so\nto speak, and the merchants are following the\nsame policy, with the result that most of them have\nthe lowest stocks in years.\nIt is on this fact that more optimistic prophets are\npredicting a real business revival this fall. They be\nlieve that when the people, with restored confidence,\nstart buying there will be an upswing in prices fol\nlowed by a demand that will bring a sudden and un\nexpected revival of business. Whether this theory\nwill prove true remains to be seen, but at any rate\nthe depletion of stocks in the hands of the merchants\nis a favorable sign.\nAnother favorable sign is found in the check in the\nrapid decline in commodity prices. For many months\ncommodity prices have been going down. But in\nAugust there was a sudden slowing of this downward\nmovement, and now it seems that the declines, with\na few notable exceptions, have been checked and that\nwe are again in a state of price stabilization. When\nthe upturn will come depends to be seen,but whn it\ndoes come it will doubtless be accompanied by a re\nvival in business.\nOther favorable indications are present. Credit is\nplentiful and comparatively cheap. The worst of\nthe drought new T s is behind and plans have been made\nto repair damage so far as possible. The seasonable\nupswing to set in pretty soon. In the meantime it\nis well to remember that Uncle Sam still has the big\ngest and most prosperous nation in the world, and\nthat the first improvement in the world wide de\npression will doubtless be felt in the United States.\n-0\nThe drought has so dwarfed and dried the grain in\nsome sections that they are picking ready-made\ncob pipes out of the ears.\u2014Detroit News.\n_ -\u2014o\nOperations are to he resumed by an Ohio knitting\ncompany. That's wdiat the country needs\u2014getting\nback to its knitting.\u2014Dayton (Ohio) Journal.\n--\u2014o-\nIf you are not satisfied with the Eighteenth A\nmendment you can console yourself by imagining how\nmany more stein songs we might have had going\nthe radio if it hadn't been for the Volstead act.\n\u2022---o\u2014---\nV hat we would like to know is how on earth Uncle\nbam ever managed to get along before the Williams\ntown conference started giving him advice on how to\nrun his business.\n7--o\u2014---\nio stand in firm and cautious independence of all\nentanglements of the European system has bgen\ncardinal point of their policy under every administra\ntiv of their government from the peace of 1783 to\nthis day This is one of the statements of John\n(Quincy Adams which some of our modern biograph\ners are careful not to mention.\ncorn\nover\na\nCUTTING OUT RED TAPE\nPresident Hoover has requested\nofficials of the Post Office and\nTreasury Departments to cut out\nall red tape and speed up the pro\ngram on public buildings. His\nquest was made with\nre\npurpose of\nimproving employment conditions\nand was similar to his decision to\nspeed up flood control work.\nThe President hopes to set an\nexample for states, municipalities\nand individual builders to follow.\nThe President made it plain that\nhe regards rentals paid for post\noffice buildings as a waste of mon\ney. To put the government in its\nown quarters as far as feasible is\none of his ambitions.\nRADICAL CHANGES\nTRANSFORM BANKING!!\nNational Commission Sees\nChanging Opinion on Branch\nBanking Issue Studies\nGroup and Chain Banks.\nNEW YORK. Modification of\nthe attitude of bankers on the long\ndisputed branch banking question\nis forecast in a review and report\ncovering rapid changes going on in\nbanking issued here by the Eco\nnomic Policy Commission of the\nAmerican Bankers Association.\nThe report, however, after referring\nto recent proposals that national\nbanks be given branch banking\npowers within the business terri\ntory surrounding their location, de\nclares that \"we do not believe that\nso-called 'trade-area' branch bank\ning is likely to gain the support of\nany large percentage of the bank\ning fraternity.''\nThe commission says that the\n\"most important development that\nhas affected American banking in\nrecent years involves the rapid\ngrowth of multiple banking organi\nzations in the form of group, chain\nand branch banking systems,\" and\nadds that \"we present this report\nas an unprejudiced economic study\nand have no theories or policies\nto urge at this time.\" The state\nment says that the commission's\ninformation indicates there are now\n269 group or chain bank systems,\nwhich control 1,922 banks and $15,\n285,000,000 in aggregate resources,\nand that there are only six states\nand the District of Columbia where\nit does not find any group organiza\ntions.\nThe Corntryssioner's Investigation\n\"We have been in touch with the\nmanagers of many important bank\ngroups,\" the report says. \"Aside\nfrom the obvious economies of cen\ntralized operation and control a\nnumber of these organizations\nheads very frankly tell us that\nthey do not feel that the system\nhas been in operation and tested\nlong enough to justify them in\nmaking positive or sweeping state\nments as to its advantages or dis\nadvantages compared to unit bank\ning.\n\"The Banking and Currency\nCommittee of the House, which is\nconducting an investigation into\nbanking developments, has called\na number of operating heads of\nsome of the great group systems.\nThese men declared that they\nfound, tinder certain conditions,\ndefinite operating and economic ad\nvantage in both group and branch\nbanking over independent unit\nbanking. Some thought group\nbanking was only a transitional\nstage, that branch banking was\npreferable and if it were per\nmitted on an extensive enough\nscale they would change their\ngroups over to branch systems.\nOthers held that group, banking\nwas preferable.\n\"Some held that the. ideal plan\nwas a combination of the two\nwith group bank units for localities\nstrong enough to support complete\nbanking institutions and with\nbranch offices extending further into\nthe smaller places requiring bank\ning services but not large enough to\nsupport complete banks. Several\nof these who advocated multiple\nbanking declared that nevertheless\nthey believed there would always\nbe room for vigorous independent\nunit bank competitors.\nGovernment Officials Express\nViews\n\"The Comptroller of the Cur\nrency recommended that national\nbanks be given branch banking\npowers within 'trade-areas.' The\nGovernor of the Federal Reserve\nBoard appeared to be in general\nagreement with the Comptroller.\nHe said there were 24,645 banks\nand 3,547 branches, a total of 28,182\nbanking offices; that in this total,\n6,353 offices were either branches\nor bank members of groups, or\nboth, leaving 21,839 banking insti\ntutions that might be definitely\ntermed independent unit banks,\nhaving no branches and in no way\nconnected with group affiliations.\nHe said all the banks had total\nloans and investments of $58,500,\n000,000, of which the group and\nbranch systems held \u00a730,000,000,\n000, or more than half.\n\"He opposed nation-wide branch\nbanking at present but said that\nultimately if bankers became\ntrained and experienced in the\nlarger technique of 'trade-area'\nbanking he thought it would In\ntime evolve nation-wide branch\nhanking under control of relatively\nfew banks, but he did not believe\nthis would mean monopoly or lack\nof competition. He favored branch\nover group banking which, how\never, he said represented an eco\nnomic development along 'trade\narea' lines and would spread unless\nsomething else were substituted\nand thought 'trade-area' branch\nbanking would serve this purpose.\n\"It is the intention of the Com\nmission to develop its own studies\nin these questions, watch carefully\nevery move that is made and every\nhit of information that may de\nvelop in this connection and'keep\nitself prepared to give an unbiased\nand accurate statement of the facts\nof the case whenever that is de\nsired.\" the renort concludes.\nYou never hear of any kid try\ning to win an endurance record\nby sitting at a school desk.\nDriftwood\n\n\nFrom The River Of Life\nL\n\n\nBy E. P. CONWELL\n\n\n\u2014i\nPICNIC\nThe Carbon County Farmer's\nEducational and Cooperative Un\nion plan to hold a county wide pic\nnic either at Peterson's Grove or\nin Joliet some day the later part\nof this month to which the Gen\neral public, members or not. will\nbe invited.\noOo\nPROGRESS\nSound equipment is heimr in\nstalled in the Liberty Theater at\nFromberg and its formal openinc\nis planned for October 1.\noOo\nTHE PHANTOM CHARGER\nI was playing' a round of golf\non the Tiny-Mite Course with a\nfriend from out of town vesterdav\nafternoon. When we reached the\nseventeenth hole we found our\nselves with even scores and the\nsuggestion was made that we rest\na few minutes so we strolled over\non the porch of the Central Hotel\nand sat down in a couple of easv\nchairs facing the course.\n\"How do you like golf,\" I in\nquired of my adversary hv way\nof making conversation. \"Pretty\nwell\" he answered, I used to he\na blacksmith before takine- uo the\nprofession of dentistry and feel\nright at home shooting a ball thro\nugh a wagon wheel hub. You know\nwe used to pitch nickles at 'em in\nthe old days. There was one thing\ndisappointing about learning the\ngame though,\" he said, \"I had al\nways supposed that a niblick was\nsomething you eat like a pretzel\nbut find that the whole purpose of\nthe game is so that one can keen\nup his appetite in hopes that some\nday he may be able to eat pret\nzels and anything else that he\ncraves. I take it, too, that many\npeople find considerable pleasure\nin it but to my mind the golf\nand particularly the Tiny-Mite co\nurse fulfills a want and a need\nj\nthat has nothing whatever to do\nwith exercise, pleasure nr iapp\ne.tite.\nBy the way, he asked,\nhow much did the city of Red\nLodge pay Plunkett and Marino to\ninstall this course?\" \"I don't know\nwhat your driving at,\" I answered.\n\"Well you don't mean to tell me\nthat they put it in for nothing or\nfor what they might make off of\nit, do you?\" he asked. \"When I\nwas here n year ago that now\nbeautiful lot was a frog pond or\nsomething of the sort littered with\nold cartons, tin'cans and what not.\nNow look at it, the most beautiful\ngolf course in the state and vet\nyou tell me that those public spir\nited citizens did it afl gratis for\nyour otherwise beautiful city?\"\n\"Yes, they did\" I answered, and\nthen I told him that when I came\nhere ten years ago that lot was\nknown as Greenough Park, that\nin its center was a beautiful ex\npanse of water known as Virtue\nLake and that it was noted for\nmany years as the home of our\ntame frog. But one morning two\nyears ago last spring the town\nwoke up to find that the tame\nfrog was dead. After ten months\nof winter it was so happv that\nit sang for four days and nights\nand the medtfcall profession laid\nits death to acute carditis super\ninduced by complications of ly\nringitis and overwork of its vocal\norgans. Our lay population of co\nurse didn't comprehend _ the tec\nnical medical terms aforesaid and\nso they understand in their simple\nminded way that our poor frog\nsimply died of joy. You know\nbrides do that once in a while in\nstory books.\nWe decided to suspend our game\nand\" cast lots to see who was the\nvictor when we reached the nine\nteenth hole and then I related to\nhim the story of The Phantom\nCharger, explaining that it was\nwell known to every man, woman\nand child in Red Lodge and that\nsome day I hoped to publish the\nstory as a matter of interest to\nthose who live outside of the city\nand harbor, no belief in the super\nnatural. Many people are getting\nso materialistic minded since the\nlast campaign that they are los\ning faith in Santa Claus and the\ntelling or recalling of the story of\nThe Phntom Charger tends to\nkeep up their faith, political and\nmythical.\nBut before beginning the story\nof The Phantom Charger, let me\nassume you that every sentence,\nevery word of it is founded on\nfact. Its authenticity can and will\nbe verified by the affidavits of\nour leading citizens should anyone\ndoubts its truth. So, listen, friend',\nfor your are sitting near the his\ntoric ground and some day this\nscene will be celebrated in song\nand story.\nMany years ago on the lot yon\nder now occupied by the Tiny-Mite\ngolf course there stood a livery\nstable owned, operated and con\ntrolled by James Virtue who in\nthe afternoon of a useful and sun\nny (life is yet one of our venerable\nand most respected citizens. His\nstable known wherever good liv\nery horses were known, was the\nMecca toward which anyone de\nsiring a good livery turnout let\nhis fotsteps stray should he be in\nthis section of the Treasure state.\nIts fame spread far and wide for\nthe hospitality of its owner whose\nmotto was, 'they'll take you there\nand they'll bring you back,' re\nferring of course to the handsome\nsteeds that were hired out to the\ntravelling men and others desir\ning up-to-date, safe, speedy and\nsatisfying livery service.\nHe kept one horse, however,\nthat was an exception to the rule\n\u2014a rangy white gelding whose ea\nrly education for speed had been\nsadly neglected, but he was safe\nand was kept for the special use\nof spoonors and sparkers, the fore\nrunners of the neckers and potters\nof the present day. His name was\nSure Shot and perhaps you re\nmember that later a gushing, 10,\n000 bbl. a day, oil well on which a\nscore or two of Red Lodge people\nbecame millionaires was named af\nter him. \"So Sure Shot was not\nnamed the charger because of his\nspeedy proclivities?\" asked my co\nmpanion. \"No,\" I answered, \"he\nwas called the Charger, not in the\nusual exception of that term but\nbecause nearly everyone who used\nhim used to chai-ge their account\nafter doing so. Most of the elder\nbusiness men and miners and even\nmany of the farmers hereabouts\nowe their successful romantic ad\nventures to the patience and fore\nsight of Sure Shot, the Charge!'.\nHe was alow of foot, one could dr\nive him with one hand and he never\nmade more than four miles an\nhour, if the moon was shining he\nhe used to stop in the shade of the\nfirst tree he'd come to. If it wasn't\nhe'd stop anyway. He was a spec\nial favorite of the young ladies of\nhis day for if they had to walk\nback they never had to travel more\nthan two and a half or three miles.\nJust the other day, last Tuesday,\nto he exact, a well known Red\nLodge business man stopped Mr.\nVirtue on the street and handed\nhim a check for $73.66. \"How\ncome?\" asked Mr. Virtue, \"You\ndon't owe me anything that 1\nknow of.\" \"Yes, I do,\" answered\naforesaid,\" I owe you a million\nif the truth were known. Years\nago one summer evening I hired\n\"Sure Shot from you and took my\ngirl out for a drive. Oh, how I\nloved that girl. She was a perfect\nblonde with rosy cheeks, ruby lips\nand tresses of gold. The moon was\nshining and the air was balmy and\nfreighted with the delectable\nbreath of June flowers as we\nstarted on a drive that promised\nto make the pleasures of a Mid\nsummer Night's Dream seem like\nmere second hand work. Old Sure\nShot, true to his custom, stopped\nunder the first tree and there the\ntrouble started. She upbraided me\nfor not hiring a better horse and\nto make a long story short Sure\nShot balked and we both walked\nback. The next week she married\nmy successful rival and they mov\ned to Spokane. Had I been X-rayed\nmy heart would have been found\nbroke just about in two. But time\nis a great healer, eVen of hurt\nhearts. She came back here for a\nvisit the other day and I saw her\nwith her hair cut and her clo\nthes shortened up for the first\ntime. Oh, boy, how I blessed the\nmemory of old Sure Shot. No, you\nmust take the money, and wait, I\nunderstand that there is a move\nment on foot to erect a monument\nto Sure Shot in the center of the\nthoroughfare where Eleventh st\nreet intersects Broadway. If so, I\nwish to head the subscription\nlist with a contribution of $500.\"\n(To be concluded)\nSLEMP'S APPOINTMENT\nHow the appointment of C. Bas\ncom Slemp, of Virginia, as Direc\ntor General of the American Par\nticipation in the French Colonial\nExposition at Paris, by President\nHoover, has been received by his\nfellow Virginians is best told by\na clipping from tbe Ledger-Dis\npatch, an independent Democratic\nnewspaper of Norfdlk.\nAfter speaking of the \"recog\nnition which he had more than\nearned,\" that newspaper said in\npart: \"Quite apart from the po\nlitical aspects of it, Mr. Slemp's\nappointment is an admirable one.\nVirginians in general, except for\nthe disgruntled and hostile of both\nparties, will approve it, realizing\nthat the President has named an\nuncommonly able man.\"","height":"21642","width":"15858"}}
